## The Categorization Review Package

Before the formal review meetings, I prepared a categorization review package that the reviewers could evaluate independently. A good review package does not just present conclusions — it shows the work so reviewers can evaluate the reasoning, not just accept or reject the outcome.

**Contents of the review package:**

*Executive Summary (one page):*
A plain-language summary of what OpenMRS is, what data it handles, the categorization result, and the key reasoning. Written for the AO who may not have deep technical background. Leads with the patient safety and regulatory implications of the categorization — connecting the technical FIPS 199 analysis to organizational language the AO works in.

*Full FIPS 199 Analysis (from Day 44):*
The complete nine-section analysis including information types, provisional ratings, adjustment rationale for each security objective, and the formal categorization statement. This is the technical foundation that Privacy Officer and ISSO peers can evaluate in detail.

*Information Type Impact Table:*
The consolidated table from Day 35 showing all eight information types, their provisional ratings, adjusted ratings, and adjustment rationale. Provides the evidentiary basis for the overall categorization.

*Comparable System Reference:*
If MyClinic operates other systems handling sensitive data, a brief comparison showing how OpenMRS categorization is consistent with or differentiated from those systems. Helps the AO assess consistency across the portfolio.

*Categorization Approval Signature Page:*
A formal page with signature lines for each required reviewer — System Owner, Privacy Officer, Compliance Officer, and Authorizing Official. The signed page becomes the official record of approval.

