## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the circumstances leading to the **2015 Premera Blue Cross breach** — which I covered on Day 14 from the risk acceptance perspective, but want to revisit through the categorization review lens.

Premera's breach affected 11 million individuals and resulted in a $74 million settlement. Post-incident investigation revealed that an audit conducted by the Office of Personnel Management prior to the breach had identified security vulnerabilities in Premera's systems — including categorization and risk assessment gaps. The recommendations from that audit were not fully implemented before the breach occurred.

The detail relevant to today's topic: the audit findings included concerns about whether Premera's risk assessments accurately reflected the sensitivity of the data the company handled. An independent review had flagged that the organization's own assessment of its risk posture may have under-estimated the sensitivity of certain data categories — exactly the kind of gap that a robust categorization review process is designed to catch.

The Premera case illustrates that the categorization review is not just internal governance theater. External reviewers — auditors, regulators, assessors — will scrutinize how an organization assessed its own systems. A categorization that survives internal challenge and is supported by documented reasoning from multiple stakeholders is far more defensible than one that was approved without genuine review.

