## What I Am Still Thinking About

The AO pushback scenario I described above — where an AO wants Moderate for resource reasons — is a real dynamic in organizations that do not have unlimited security budgets. I want to think more carefully about how to make the case for an accurate High categorization without it becoming an adversarial conversation.

The framing I find most effective is not "here is why you are wrong to want Moderate" but "here is what Moderate means in practice for this system." Moderate means the control baseline does not include certain High-baseline controls. Which specific controls? What risk do those gaps create? What is the cost of implementing those controls compared to the cost of a breach that those controls would help prevent?

That conversation — translating the categorization decision into specific control gaps and their risk implications — is the executive communication skill that the risk register work from Day 38 supports. The AO who understands that Moderate means not requiring enhanced MFA and not requiring more rigorous contingency plan testing is better positioned to make a genuinely informed risk acceptance decision than one who hears only "Moderate vs. High."

